STRAY animals feasting on sewage could result in people getting seriously ill. Animals such as pigs are being exposed to dirty water in Nelson Mandela Bay Municipality.Worried residents from Wells Estate, Port Elizabeth told Daily Sun: “Most of the dirty water is caused by overflowing sewage . The municipality takes a long time to fix the problem and it looks like there is no permanent solution.if(typeof za24_DisplayAd != "undefined") za24_DisplayAd("300x250","2");<a href="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" target="_blank"><img src="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" border="0" alt=""></a>“When we slaughter and eat the meat, we do not ask where it came from and the same goes when we buy expired meat without question.”Municipal spokesman Mthubanzi Mniki told Daily Sun: “The animal control unit under the environmental management sub-directorate educates owners about diseases that may be passed from animals to humans, known as zoo- notic diseases.“Meetings are held with those affected by roaming animals, including owners, the traffic and human settlements departments and urban agriculture,” Mniki said. “The aim is to educate owners about accidents and diseases. The municipality wants them to be responsible and keep animals safe. Animals on public municipal roads may be impounded.”